node.text: Sopes are rounds of griddled masa with a little rim around the edge to hold delicious fillings. “In my house, sopes were always filled with refried black beans, pulled chicken, chopped romaine lettuce, crema, crumbled fresh cheese, and then one or two salsas and guacamole or avocado to top,” writes Epi contributor @Fanygerson. But sopes are made to be customized, she says. Learn the cooking method in the video above, and check out the link in our bio to get the recipe.

node.text: Gorditas are one of the most popular street foods in Mexico. According to @fanygerson, the translation means “little fatties,” and they’re thick masa pockets that are toasted on a comal, then stuffed with fillings. Watch the video to learn all of Gerson’s tips and tricks, then click the link in our bio for the recipe—and a sweet variation, too.

node.text: You can find tlacoyos all across Mexico—and they’re one of @fanygerson’s favorite street food snacks. The thick oval-shaped masa patties are crispy on the outside, stuffed with beans or other fillings, and piled high with a refreshing cactus salad. Here, Fany shows you how to make them, step by step, to devour right away or stock your freezer. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio.

node.text: “For many families, making tamales is a ritual, and younger and older generations each have specific roles in the process,” writes Epi contributor, chef @fanygerson. Here, Gerson walks you through the whole method, step by step, so you can make the fluffiest, most flavorful tamales of your life. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio.

node.text: When chef and cookbook author Fany Gerson (@fanygerson) first moved to New York from Mexico over 20 years ago, it wasn’t a matter of *wanting* to find good tortillas—she *needed* them. Mass-produced tortillas from supermarkets and delis had nothing in common with the supple, fragrant fresh tortillas she knew and loved in Mexico. So she started making her own—now she’s here to share her tips, step by step. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio. Director: @c.emanuelsmith DP: @bendewster Editor: @elliottjchrist

node.text: One day, you will be in a market, and you will pass the coconuts. They will grab your attention. You'll say to yourself, "I'm going to buy this coconut." You settle at the register, and bring your groceries home. You put most of them away. As you hold up that last item, you will ask yourself: "Why did I buy this coconut?" At least we can help answer how to open it!

node.title: 50 People Try to Crack Open a Coconut

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 07, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Chewy, flaky bread is always a crowd-pleaser. "Paratha is just fun. It’s pull-apart bread!" says @flybyjing founder Jing Gao (@jingtheory) who pairs paratha with steamed pork belly and crispy fish fragrant eggplant to make the ideal comfort food menu. While the paratha is fantastic on its own, it’s even better when you use it to sop up the juices from the pork and eggplant. Try the recipe and get the full menu at the link in bio.  Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @lililbeijing

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 06, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: Grapes with chicken? Absolutely. Instead of braising your bird in wine, use red or green table grapes to add just the right amount of acidity to this easy, super savory dish. Fennel and honey add sweetness, while Calabrian chile paste and red wine vinegar liven up the braising liquid. Try it tonight after checking out the link in bio. Photo and Food Styling @j_deleo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 06, 2021. May be an image of dessert.

node.text: This is the best cheesecake recipe, period. Or so claims former Epi food editor Anna Stockwell (@acstockwell) who says, "I am fully comfortable in my confidence that it's the only cheesecake recipe anybody needs." Is the Three Cities of Spain Cheesecake truly the best cheesecake of all time? Check out the link in bio to try it for yourself—and let us know if you agree. Photo @calebleeadams, Food Styling @acstockwell

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 05, 2021. May be an image of dessert.

node.text: Forgive a terrible pun, but these easy bakes are a piece of cake. This orange chocolate loaf cake comes together quickly in a stand mixer and uses whipped cream in place of butter, saving you a step. For more ideas, we've collected 59 of our unfussiest cake recipes for you to bake over the long weekend. Try your hand at a no-bake cheesecake, a classic bundt, or a simple upside-down cherry cake. Find them all (and more!) at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @acstockwell

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 04, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text: Ace your coffee game this season. Just in case you’ve been looking to upgrade your grinder, Epi has put together a detailed list of the best models around. We've got grinders for all budgets and needs, including manual versions and grinders made for espresso. Get a better buzz and check out the array of options at the link in bio. Photo @travis.rainey

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 03, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Don't wait until the temperature drops to try out this riff on a classic Caprese salad. Need even more ideas for what to do with your end-of-summer cherry tomato haul? Sauté them until they burst and then toss with pasta, marinate them to serve in salads, or cook them low and slow to slather on everything. Check out all 59 of Epi's best cherry tomato recipes at the link in bio. Photo @yungbludlau

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 03, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: This soup from Epi contributor Christian Reynoso (@christianreynoso) is summer in a bowl. A variation on caldo de queso, the soup starts with a warm, tomato-y broth that gets filled with zucchini, potatoes, and peppers, plus pops of delicious queso fresco. Savor your summer veg and try this deeply satisfying (yet remarkably light) soup after checking out the recipe at the link in bio. ​Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @curlygirlcook

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 02, 2021. May be an image of drink, indoor and text that says 'ko SPARKLING MANGO WATER LYCHEE SPARKLING WAT Made with rea fruit. No added sugar. 12FL Oz (355 ML)'.

node.text: Autumn is already on the horizon, but these refreshing sodas are perfect for keeping you in a summer groove. "All the Sanzo flavors are good, but the lychee version is perfect," says Epi associate food editor Kendra Vaculin (@kendrakendrakendra). If you're looking to go head-first into fall, we've also got outdoor warming solutions that'll be great for cozy season. Head over to the link in bio to see more of our end-of-summer/beginning-of-fall shopping picks. Photo @j_deleo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 02, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: In a dinner rut? Break out of it with juicy, flavorful pork chops. Try a bright, tangy marinade full of pickled vegetables to contrast thick, fatty pork. Pile strips of pan-seared boneless pork chops onto a bed of rice noodles drenched in a basil-lime sauce. Add seared plums with your chops, along with a splash of lemon and some grilled halloumi to round it out. Check out all 41 recipes at the link in bio. Photo by @j_deleo, @chelsealouisekyle, @yungbludlau, Prop Styling @acstockwell, @emilyeisen, Food Styling  @j_deleo, @susietheodorou

node.text: It’s a cabbage, but it’s also a tree. Sometimes called cow cabbage, long jacks, or Jersey cabbage, this rare giant kale cultivar is by far the strangest member of the wild cabbage family. The plant can grow over 10 feet tall, and its strong, slender stalk makes it a prime candidate for a good walking stick (thus its other nickname, walking stick kale). The greens are delicious, too—treat them as you would kale. Read more about this very large brassica and get your seeds now at the link in bio. Illustration @juliarothman

If you’re not making your own flour tortillas, what’s stopping you? All you need is flour, fat, salt, water, and a rolling pin.

“A good tortilla should be a nice vehicle for the taco: thin and light and chewy, and then you can put less filling in it and everything becomes a much more delicate thing to eat,” says Danny Mena (@dannyhecho). 

If your tortillas aren’t puffing, simply double check your griddle temperature and make sure you’re working with the right ratio of flour to fat! For more tips from Mena, including ​​why you should make your tortilla dough hours (or even days) in advance, check out the link in bio. Photo and Food Styling @j_deleo
